formula: {(p-1)/2, p, 2p+1, 4p+3, 8p+7, 16p+15, 32p+31} = {nonprime, prime, prime, prime, prime, prime, composite}

A059765.name: Possible sizes of the torsion group of an elliptic curve over the rationals Q. This is a finite sequence.
formula: Numbers n such that A221362(n) > 0. - _Jonathan Sondow_, May 10 2014

A059766.name: Initial (unsafe) primes of Cunningham chains of first type with length exactly 6.

A059767.name: Initial (unsafe) primes of Cunningham chains of first type with length exactly 7.
formula: p primes, (2^k)*p+(2^k)-1 is prime too for k=0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 and is composite for k=-1 and k=7.

A059768.name: Numbers k such that 2*3^k + 35 is prime.

A059769.name: Frobenius number of the subsemigroup of the natural numbers generated by successive pairs of Fibonacci numbers.
formula: a(n) = (F(n)-1)*(F(n+1)-1)-1 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.

A059770.name: First solution of x^2 = 2 mod p for primes p such that a solution exists.
formula: a(n) = first (least) solution of x^2 = 2 mod p, where p is the n-th prime such that x^2 = 2 mod p has a solution, i.e. p is the n-th term of A038873.

A059771.name: Second solution of x^2 = 2 mod p for primes p such that a solution exists.
formula: a(n) = second (larger) solution of x^2 = 2 mod p, where p is the n-th prime such that x^2 = 2 mod p has a solution, i.e. p is the n-th term of A038873. a(n) = 0 if x^2 = 2 mod p has one solution (only for p = 2).

A059772.name: Smallest prime p such that n is a solution mod p of x^2 = 2, or 0 if no such prime exists.
formula: If n^2-2 has a (unique) prime factor p > n, then a(n) = p, else a(n) = 0.

A059773.name: Maximum size of Aut(G) where G is a finite group of order n.

A059774.name: Consider the line segment in R^n from the origin to the point P=(1,2,3,...,n); let d = squared distance to this line from the closest point of Z^n (excluding the endpoints). Sequence gives d times P.P.

A059775.name: From solution to a counting problem.

A059776.name: Three-quadrant Ferrers graphs that partition n.

A059777.name: Number of self-conjugate three-quadrant Ferrers graphs that partition n.
formula: G.f.: 1/((1+x)*G(0)), where G(k)= 1 - x^(2*k+1)/(1 - x^(2*k+2)/(x^(2*k+2) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 20 2013
G.f.: conjecture: 1/(Q(0) - 1), where Q(k) = 1 + (-x)^k - (-x)^(k+2)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 25 2013
G.f.: Sum_{k>=0} x^(2*k) * Product_{j=1..k} (1+x^(2*j-1))/(1-x^(2*j)). - _Seiichi Manyama_, Jul 11 2018

A059779.name: A Lucas triangle: T(m,n), m >= n >= 0.

A059780.name: A generalized Pascal triangle of order 3: T(n,m), n >= 0, 2*n >= m >= 0.
formula: T(n, m) = T(n-1, m-2) + T(n-1, m-1) + T(n-1, m) - 2*T(n-2, m-2). In words, each entry is the sum of 3 entries above it (i.e., in the previous row) minus twice the entry two rows above it.

A059781.name: Triangle T(n,k) giving exponent of power of 2 dividing entry (n,k) of trinomial triangle A027907.

A059782.name: Triangle T(n,k) giving exponent of power of 3 dividing entry (n,k) of trinomial triangle A027907.

A059783.name: Number of paths (without loops) in graph of n-dimensional hypercube starting at point (0,0,0,...,0) and ending at (1,1,1,...,1).

A059784.name: a(n+1) = nextprime(a(n)^2). Smallest prime following the square of previous prime. Initial value = 2.

A059785.name: a(n+1) = prevprime(a(n)^2). Largest prime prior to the square of previous prime. Initial value = 2.

A059786.name: Smallest prime after 2*(n-th prime).
formula: a(n) = A117928(n,1) for n>1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 03 2006

A059787.name: Distance between 2*(n-th prime) and next prime.

A059790.name: Distance between 2*(n-th prime) and nearest prime.

A059791.name: Numbers n such that floor(phi^n) is prime, where phi = golden ratio.

A059792.name: Numbers n such that floor(Pi^n) is prime.

A059793.name: Stationary value of quotient in the continued fraction expansion of sqrt(prime) when the quotient-cycle-length = 1.
formula: a(n) = 2*A005574(n). For n=sqrt(p) the transient is n, the stationary quotient is 2n.

A059794.name: a(n) = n* - 2^(n-1), where n* (A003418) = least common multiple of the numbers [1,...,n].

A059795.name: Numbers n such that n^2 starts with the reverse of n.

A059796.name: Degrees of irreducible representations of symmetric group S_14.

A059797.name: Second in a series of arrays counting standard tableaux by partition type.
formula: T(row, col) = T(row-1, col-1) + T(row-1, col) + A007318(row+2, col+1). - Corrected by _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 27 2011

A059798.name: Primes p such that |p - q| is a square, where q is the reversal of p.
formula: Subtract reversal of prime from prime. Take absolute value. If a square, add to sequence.

A059799.name: Primes which when added to their reversals are squares.
formula: Add prime to its reverse. If a square, add to sequence.

A059800.name: Smallest prime p such that the quotient-cycle length in continued fraction expansion of sqrt(p) is n: smallest prime p(m) for which A054269(m)=n.
formula: a(n) = Min{p|A054269(sequence number of p)=n; p is prime}.

A059801.name: Numbers n such that 4^n - 3^n is prime.

A059802.name: Numbers n such that 5^n - 4^n is prime.

A059803.name: Numbers n such that 9^n - 8^n is prime or a strong pseudoprime.

A059804.name: Consider the line segment in R^n from the origin to the point v=(2,3,5,7,11,...) with prime coordinates; let d = squared distance to this line from the closest point of Z^n (excluding the endpoints). Sequence gives d times v.v.

A059805.name: Natural numbers written with digits grouped in pairs and leading zeros omitted.

A059806.name: Minimal size of the center of G where G is a finite group of order n.
formula: For prime p and m >= 3, a(p^m) = p. - _Eric M. Schmidt_, Aug 27 2012

A059807.name: Maximal size of the commutator subgroup of G where G is a finite group of order n.
formula: For prime p and m >= 2, a(p^m) = p^(m - 2). - _Eric M. Schmidt_, Sep 20 2012

A059808.name: Numbers which contain the same digits in two different bases.

A059809.name: Numbers that do not contain exactly the same digits in two different smaller bases.

A059810.name: Numbers k such that 5*7^k + 6 is prime.

A059811.name: Let g_n be the ball packing n-width for the manifold torus X interval; sequence gives numerator of (g_n/Pi)^2.

A059812.name: Let g_n be the ball packing n-width for the manifold torus X interval; sequence gives denominator of (g_n/Pi)^2.

A059813.name: Let s_n be the simplex packing n-width for the manifold torus X interval; sequence gives numerator of s_n/Pi.

A059814.name: Let s_n be the simplex packing n-width for the manifold torus X interval; sequence gives denominator of s_n/Pi.

A059815.name: Let g_n be the ball packing n-width for the manifold torus X square; sequence gives numerator of (g_n/Pi)^2.

A059816.name: Let g_n be the ball packing n-width for the manifold torus X square; sequence gives denominator of (g_n/Pi)^2.
formula: Apparently, for n>8, a(2n) = 2n-1, a(2n+1) = n. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 29 2004

A059817.name: Let s_n be the simplex packing n-width for the manifold torus X square; sequence gives numerator of s_n/Pi.

A059818.name: Let s_n be the simplex packing n-width for the manifold torus X square; sequence gives denominator of s_n/Pi.

A059819.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. Sum_{t>0} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^2 *Product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).
formula: G.f.: (F(x)+G(x)^2)/2, where F(x) = Sum_{k>0} (k+1)*x^k/(1-x^k) and G(x) = Sum_{k>0} x^k/(1-x^k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 12 2004

A059820.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. Sum_{t>0} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^3 *Product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).

A059821.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. sum_{t>0} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^4 *product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).

A059822.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. sum_{t>0} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^5 *product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).

A059823.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. sum_{t>0} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^6 *product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).

A059824.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. Sum_{t>=1} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^7 * Product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).

A059825.name: Expansion of series related to Liouville's Last Theorem: g.f. sum_{t>0} (-1)^(t+1) *x^(t*(t+1)/2) / ( (1-x^t)^8 *product_{i=1..t} (1-x^i) ).

A059826.name: a(n) = (n^2 - n + 1)*(n^2 + n + 1).
formula: a(n) = (n^2-n+1) * (n^2+n+1) = A002061(n) * A002061(n+1), products of two consecutive central polygonal numbers. a(n) = (n^6-1)/(n^2-1), n>1. a(n) = (n^5-n^4+n^3-n^2+n-1)/(n-1) = A062159(n)/(n-1), n>1. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Apr 12 2006
a(n) = A219069(n,1), for n > 0. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Nov 11 2012
a(n+2) = (n^2+3n+3) * (n^2+5n+7) = (t(n)+t(n+2)) * (t(n+1)+t(n+3)), where t=A000217 are triangular numbers. For n>=1, a(n+2) = t(2*t(n+2)+t(n)) -t(t(n)-1). - _J. M. Bergot_, Nov 29 2012

A059827.name: Cubes of triangular numbers: (n*(n+1)/2)^3.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{j=1..n} Sum_{i=1..n} i*j^3. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Jun 25 2006

A059828.name: Numbers which contain exactly the same digits (with the correct multiplicity) in 3 different smaller bases.

A059829.name: Maximal size of a minimal-generating-set of G where G is a finite group of order n.

A059831.name: Determinant of Wilkinson's eigenvalue test matrix of order 2n+1.

A059832.name: A ternary tribonacci triangle: form the triangle as follows: start with 3 single values: 1, 2, 3. Each succeeding row is a concatenation of the previous 3 rows.

A059833.name: "Madonna's Sequence": add 1 (mod 10) to each digit of Pi.

A059834.name: Sum of squares of entries of Wilkinson's eigenvalue test matrix of order 2n+1.
formula: a(n) = (2n^3 + 3n^2 + 13n)/3. For the matrix of order 2n, the formula is (4n^3 + 23n - 12)/6 (which is not integer-valued). - _David Wasserman_, May 24 2002

A059835.name: Form triangle as follows: start with three single digits: 0, 1, 2. Each succeeding row is a concatenation of the previous three rows.

A059837.name: Diagonal T(s,s) of triangle A059836.
formula: T(s, s) = (s-1)^2 * T(s-1, s-1) / floor(s/2) - Larry Reeves.
a(n)=sum{k=0..n, (-1)^(n+k)C(n, k)sum{i=0..n, C(n, floor(i/2))k^i} } - _Paul Barry_, Aug 05 2004
E.g.f. is the integral of the o.g.f. of A001405. With offset 0: e.g.f. is o.g.f. of A001405.

A059838.name: Number of permutations in the symmetric group S_n that have even order.

A059840.name: a(n) = F(n)*F(n-1) if n odd otherwise F(n)*F(n-1)-1, where F = Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: G.f.: (x^3)*(2-x)/((1-x^2)*(1-3*x+x^2)), with a(0):=0. See a comment on A080144. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jul 30 2012
a(n) = floor(1/(Sum_{k>=n} 1/Fibonacci(k)^2)) [Ohtsuka and Nakamura]. - _Michel Marcus_, Aug 09 2018
For n > 2, 2 * A000217(a(n)) = A228873(n-2). - _Diego Rattaggi_, Jan 27 2021

A059841.name: Period 2: Repeat [1,0]. a(n) = 1 - (n mod 2).
formula: Additive with a(p^e) = 1 if p = 2, 0 otherwise.
a(n) = (sin((n+1)*Pi/2))^2 = (cos(n*Pi/2))^2 with n >= 0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Nov 17 2006
a(n) = sum(k = 1..n, (-1)^(n-k) ) for n > 0. - _William A. Tedeschi_, Aug 05 2011
E.g.f.: cosh(x) = 1 + x^2/(Q(0) - x^2); Q(k) = 8k + 2 + x^2/(1 + (2k + 1)*(2k + 2)/Q(k + 1)); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 21 2011
E.g.f.: cosh(x) = 1/2*Q(0); Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x^2/(x^2 + (2k + 1)*(2k + 2)/Q(k + 1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 21 2011
E.g.f.: cosh(x) = E(0)/(1-x) where E(k) = 1 - x/(1 - x/(x - (2*k+1)*(2*k+2)/E(k+1) )); (continued fraction ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 05 2013
For the general case: the characteristic function of numbers that are not multiples of m is a(n) = floor((n-1)/m) - floor(n/m) + 1, m,n > 0. - _Boris Putievskiy_, May 08 2013

A059842.name: The next square after a(n)^3 is a(n+1)^2.
formula: a(n+1) = floor(sqrt(a(n)^3)) + 1. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Mar 22 2001

A059843.name: a(n) is the smallest prime p such that p-n is a nonzero square.
formula: a(n) = min{p : p - n = x^2 for some x > 0, p is prime}.
Does a(n) exist for all n? - _Jianing Song_, Feb 04 2019

A059844.name: a(n) = smallest nonzero square x^2 such that n+x^2 is prime.
formula: a(n) + n is the smallest prime of the form x^2 + n.

A059846.name: Smallest p primes which give q=2p+2n-1 primes. Smallest Sophie Germain primes generalized in a possible way: 1 is replaced by 2n-1.

A059847.name: a(n)=2*p+2n-1, the smallest prime q such that p=[q-(2n-1)]/2 is prime. A special generalization of safe primes: 1 is replaced with 2n-1.
formula: Min{p|p and q=(p-2n+1)/2, p and q are primes}

A059848.name: As a square table by antidiagonals, the n-digit number which in base k starts 1010101...

A059849.name: Number of pairs of partitions of {1,2,...,n} whose meet is the partition {{1}, {2}, ..., {n}}.
formula: E.g.f. M(x) satisfies the equation M(exp(x)-1) = sum_{n >= 0)} (B_n)^2 * x^n/n!, where B_n is the n-th Bell number (A000110).
E.g.f.: Sum_{n>=0} exp( (1+x)^n - 2 ) / n!. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 24 2018
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling1(n, k)*Bell(k)^2. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 01 2003

A059851.name: a(n) = n - floor(n/2) + floor(n/3) - floor(n/4) + ... (this is a finite sum).
formula: a(n) = A006218(n)-2*A006218(floor(n/2)). G.f.: 1/(1-x)*Sum_{n>=1} x^n/(1+x^n). Partial sums of A048272. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 15 2002
a(n) = Sum_{n/2 < k < =n} d(k) - Sum_{1 < =k <= n/2} d(k), where d(k) = A000005(k). Also, a(n) = number of terms among {floor(n/k)}, 1<=k<=n, that are odd. - _Leroy Quet_, Jan 19 2006
a(n) =  Sum_{k=1..n} round(n/(2*k)) - floor(n/(2*k)), where round(1/2)=1. (End)

A059852.name: Consider the English alphabet in the International Morse radio telegraph code. Map a 'dit' to the digit one and a 'dah' to the digit 2, then express that ternary number in decimal.

A059853.name: Period of continued fraction for sqrt(n^2+3), n >= 2.
formula: If n is a multiple of 3 then a(n) = 2.

A059854.name: Period of continued fraction for sqrt(n^2+5), n >= 3.
formula: If n is a multiple of 5 then a(n) = 2.

A059855.name: Period of continued fraction for sqrt(n^2+4), n >= 1.
formula: a(n) = 2 for even n, a(n) = 5 for odd n > 1.

A059856.name: Write down decimal expansion of Euler-Mascheroni constant gamma (A001620); divide up into minimal chunks so that chunks have increasing length and do not begin with zero.

A059857.name: Alternating clock-face numbers.
formula: If you start with 12 on a clock's face and move forward 1 it yields the number 1, then moving backward 2 yields 11, then moving forward 3 yields 2, moving backward 4 yields 10 and so forth.

A059858.name: Primes p such that x^5 == 2 (mod p) has five solutions.

A059859.name: Sum of squares of first n quarter-squares (A002620).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} floor(i^2/4)^2). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Mar 20 2012

A059860.name: a(n) = binomial(n+1, 2)^5.
formula: L(n) = ((n^m)(n + 1)^m)/(2^m) where m is the dimension.

A059861.name: a(n) = Product_{i=2..n} (prime(i) - 2).
formula: a(n) = Det[ DiagonalMatrix[ Table[ Prime[i-1] - 2, {i, 2, n} ] ] + 1 ] for n>1. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, May 21 2006

A059862.name: a(n) = Product_{i=3..n} (prime(i) - 3).
formula: a(1) = a(2) = 1, a(3) = 2; a(n + 1) = a(n) * (prime(n) - 3) for n >= 3. - _David A. Corneth_, Jul 15 2018

A059864.name: a(n) = Product_{i=4..n} (prime(i)-5), where prime(i) is i-th prime.

A059866.name: Period length of the continued fraction for sqrt(2^n-1).

A059867.name: Number of irreducible representations of the symmetric group S_n that have odd degree.
formula: If n = sum 2^e[i] in binary, then the number of odd degree irreducible complex representations of S_n is 2^sum e[i]. In words: write n in binary and take the product of the powers of 2 that appear.
G.f.: prod(k>=0, 1 + 2^k * x^2^k). a(n) = 2^A073642(n). - _Ralf Stephan_, Jun 02 2003

A059868.name: There exist no palindromic pentagonal numbers of length a(n).

A059869.name: Numbers k such that there exist no palindromic heptagonals of length k.

A059870.name: Numbers n such that there exist no palindromic octagonal numbers of length n.

A059871.name: Number of solutions to the equation p_i = (1+mod(i,2))*p_{i-1} +- p_{i-2} +- p_{i-3} +- ... +- 2 +- 1, where p_i is the i-th prime number (where p_1 = 2 and the "zeroth prime" p_0 is defined to be 1).

A059872.name: Solutions to the equation given in A059871, encoded as binary vectors and converted to decimal.

A059873.name: The lexicographically earliest sequence of binary encodings of solutions satisfying the equation given in A059871.

A059874.name: The lexicographically earliest sequence of binary encodings of solutions satisfying the equation p_i = (1+mod(i,2))*p_{i-1} +- p_{i-2} +- p_{i-3} +- ... +- 2 + 1, where p_i is the i-th prime number.

A059875.name: The lexicographically last sequence of binary encodings of solutions satisfying the equation given in A059871.

A059877.name: Those n for which the absolute value of A059876[n] is prime.

A059878.name: a(n) = bin_prime_sum(fibonacci(A001651[n])), where fibonacci(A001651[n]) is A014437[n]

A059879.name: Those n for which the absolute value of A059878[n] is prime.

A059880.name: Positions of negative terms in A059876.

A059881.name: As upper right triangle: wiggly sums to n where first term is k (sums in which terms alternately increase and decrease or vice versa; zigzag and zagzig partitions).

A059882.name: As upper right triangle: ascending wiggly sums to n where first term is k (sums in which terms alternately increase and decrease; zigzag partitions).
formula: If n>k>0 T(n, k)=sum_j[S(n-k, j)] over j>k and if n>0 T(n, n)=1; where S(n, k)=A059883(n, k) and if n>k>0, S(n, k)=sum_j[T(n-k, j)] over k>j (note reversal) and if n>0 S(n, n)=1.

A059883.name: As upper right triangle: descending wiggly sums to n where first term is k (sums in which terms alternately decrease and increase; zagzig partitions).
formula: If n>k>0 T(n, k)=sum_j[S(n-k, j)] over k>j and if n>0 T(n, n)=1; where S(n, k)=A059882(n, k) and if n>k>0, S(n, k)=sum_j[T(n-k, j)] over j>k (note reversal) and if n>0 S(n, n)=1.

A059884.name: Prime factorization of n encoded by recursively interleaving bits of successive prime exponents.

A059885.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 3 mod m = n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{ d divides n } mu(n/d)*tau(3^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059886.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 4 mod m=n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{ d divides n } mu(n/d)*tau(4^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059887.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 5 mod m=n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} mu(n/d)*tau(5^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059888.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 6 mod m=n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{ d divides n } mu(n/d)*tau(6^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059889.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 7 mod m=n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} mu(n/d)*tau(7^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059890.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 8 mod m=n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{ d divides n } mu(n/d)*tau(8^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059891.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 9 mod m=n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} mu(n/d)*tau(9^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059892.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of 10 mod m is equal to n}|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} mu(n/d)*tau(10^d-1), (mu(n) = Moebius function A008683, tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005).

A059893.name: Reverse the order of all but the most significant bit in binary expansion of n: if n = 1ab..yz then a(n) = 1zy..ba.
formula: a(n) = A030109(n) + A053644(n). If 2*2^k<=n<3*2^k then a(n) = 2*a(n-2^k); if 3*2^k <= n < 4*2^k then a(n) = 1 + a(n-2^k) starting with a(1)=1. - _Henry Bottomley_, Sep 13 2001

A059894.name: Complement and reverse the order of all but the most significant bit in binary expansion of n. n = 1ab..yz -> 1ZY..BA = a(n), where A = 1-a, B = 1-b, ... .
formula: a(1) = 1, a(2n) = a(n) + 2^(floor(log_2(n))+1), a(2n+1) = a(n) + 2^floor(log_2(n)) (conjectured). - _Ralf Stephan_, Aug 21 2003

To verify first conjecture above we use n = Sum_{k=0..l(n)} T(n,k)*2^k where l(n) = floor(log_2(n)), T(n,k) = floor(n/2^k) mod 2, so by definition we have a(n) = Sum_{k=0..l(n)} (1-T(n,k-1))*2^(l(n)-k), then we use l(n) = l(floor(n/2)) + 1, T(2n,k) = T(n,k-1), T(2n+1,k) = T(n,k-1) + [k=0] and apply shifting of the summation. - _Mikhail Kurkov_, Nov 11 2019

A059895.name: Table a(i,j) = product prime[k]^(Ei[k] AND Ej[k]) where Ei and Ej are the vectors of exponents in the prime factorizations of i and j; AND is the bitwise operation on binary representation of the exponents.

A059896.name: Table a(i,j) = product prime(k)^(Ei(k) OR Ej(k)) where Ei and Ej are the vectors of exponents in the prime factorizations of i and j; OR is the bitwise operation on binary representation of the exponents.

A059897.name: Square array read by antidiagonals: T(i,j) = product prime(k)^(Ei(k) XOR Ej(k)) where Ei and Ej are the vectors of exponents in the prime factorizations of i and j; XOR is the bitwise operation on binary representation of the exponents.
formula: For all x, y >= 1, A(x,y) * A059895(x,y)^2 = x*y. - _Antti Karttunen_, Apr 11 2017
if A(n,k_1) = n * k_1 and A(n,k_2) = n * k_2 then A(n, A(k_1,k_2)) = n * A(k_1,k_2)
T(k, m) = k*m for coprime k and m. - _David A. Corneth_, Apr 03 2019
if A(nm,m) = n, A(nm,k) = A(n,k) * A(m,k) / k. - _Peter Munn_, Apr 04 2019

A059899.name: Primes p such that x^3 = 2 has more than one solution mod p and the sum of the (three) solutions is p.

A059900.name: Successively interleaved alternate bits in binary expansion of n gives vector of exponents in prime factorization of a(n).

A059901.name: Partitions encoded by prime factorization. The partition [P1+P2+P3+...] with P1>=P2>=P3>=... is encoded as 2^P1 * 3^P2 * 5^P3 *...

A059902.name: Partitions encoded by interleaving bits in parts. The partition [P1+P2+P3+...] with P1>=P2>=P3>=... is encoded in binary by recursively interleaving the bits of P1 with the (recursively interleaved bits of P2 with the (recursively...)).

A059903.name: Periodic part of continued fraction for sqrt(n), encoded by raising successive primes to the terms. If sqrt(n)=c0+[c1,c2,c3...] then a(n)=2^c1*3^c2*5^c3*...

A059904.name: Periodic part of continued fraction for sqrt(n), encoded by recursively interleaving the bits in the binary expansions of the repeating terms.

A059905.name: Index of first half of decomposition of integers into pairs based on A000695.
formula: To get a(n), write n as Sum b_j*2^j, then a(n) = Sum b_(2j)*2^j. - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Nov 13 2008

A059906.name: Index of second half of decomposition of integers into pairs based on A000695.
formula: To get a(n), write n as Sum b_j*2^j, then a(n) = Sum b_(2j+1)*2^j. - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Nov 13 2008
a(n) = Sum_{k>=0} A030308(n,k)*b(k) with b(0)=0 and b(k)=A077957(k-1) for k>0. - _Philippe Deléham_, Oct 18 2011
Conjecture: a(n) = n - Sum(k=1..n, sqrt(2)^A007814(k)+(-sqrt(2))^A007814(k))/2 = -Sum(k=1..n, (-1)^k * 2^floor(k/2) * floor(n/2^k)). - _Velin Yanev_, Dec 01 2016

A059907.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = 2}|.
formula: a(n) = tau(n^2-1)-tau(n-1), where tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005. Generally, if b(n, r) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = r}| then b(n, r) = Sum_{d|r} mu(d)*tau(n^(r/d)-1), where mu(n) = Moebius function A008683.

A059908.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = 3}|.
formula: a(n) = tau(n^3-1)-tau(n-1), where tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005. Generally, if b(n, r) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = r}| then b(n, r) = Sum_{d|r} mu(d)*tau(n^(r/d)-1), where mu(n) = Moebius function A008683.

A059909.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = 4}|.
formula: a(n) = tau(n^4-1)-tau(n^2-1), where tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005. More generally, if b(n, r) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = r}| then b(n, r) = Sum_{d|r} mu(d)*tau(n^(r/d)-1), where mu(n) = Moebius function A008683.

A059910.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = 5}|.
formula: a(n) = tau(n^5-1)-tau(n-1), where tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005. Generally, if b(n, r) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = r}| then b(n, r) = Sum_{d|r} mu(d)*tau(n^(r/d)-1), where mu(n) = Moebius function A008683.

A059911.name: a(n) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = 6}|.
formula: a(n) = tau(n^6-1)-tau(n^3-1)-tau(n^2-1)+tau(n-1), where tau(n) = number of divisors of n A000005. Generally, if b(n, r) = |{m : multiplicative order of n mod m = r}| then b(n, r) = Sum_{d|r} mu(d)*tau(n^(r/d)-1), where mu(n) = Moebius function A008683.

A059912.name: Triangle T(n,k) of orders of n degree irreducible polynomials over GF(2) listed in ascending order, k=1..A059499(n).
formula: T(n,k) = k-th smallest element of M(n) = {d : d|(2^n-1)} \ U(n-1) with U(n) = M(n) union U(n-1) if n>0, U(0) = {}. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Jun 01 2012

A059913.name: Triangle T(n,k) of numbers of n degree irreducible polynomials over GF(2) which have order A059912(n,k), k=1..A059499(n).
formula: T(n,k) = phi(A059912(n,k))/n, where phi = Euler totient function A000010.

A059914.name: Primes p such that x^3 = 2 has more than one solution mod p and the sum of the (three) solutions is 2*p.

A059915.name: A sequence f(n) of positive integers is called an F-sequence (in memory of Fibonacci) if it satisfies f(0)=0, f(1)=1, f(2)=2 and for all n > 2, either f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-2) or f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-3). A positive integer is called an F-number if it occurs in any F-sequence. Sequence gives numbers which are not F-numbers.

A059916.name: Nonnegative integers that when written out in full in English have no repeated letter.

A059919.name: Generalized Fermat numbers: 3^(2^n)+1, n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*...*a(1)*a(0) + 2, n >= 0, where for n = 0, we get 2*(empty product, i.e., 1) + 2 = 4 = a(0).
The above formula implies the GCD of any pair of terms is 2, which means that the terms of (3^(2^n)+1)/2 (A059917) are pairwise coprime. - _Daniel Forgues_, Jun 20 & 22 2011

A059920.name: If m/n = q + r/n (r < n, n,m >=1), then array a(m,n) = qr (meaning q followed by r). Read by antidiagonals.

A059922.name: Each term in the table is the product of the two terms above it + 1.

A059923.name: a(n+1) is smallest number with a(n+1)^n > a(n)^(n+1).
formula: a(n+1) = floor( a(n)^(1+1/n) ) + 1; compare A080870. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Feb 21 2003
a(n) = floor(x^n), where x=1.53885131519173... - _Paul D. Hanna_, Feb 21 2003

A059924.name: Write the numbers from 1 to n^2 in a spiraling square; a(n) is the total of the sums of the two diagonals.

A059925.name: Numbers n such that {n, n+2, n+6, n+8, n+30, n+32, n+36, n+38} are all prime.

A059926.name: Length of period of the continued fraction expansion of sqrt(2^n+1).

A059927.name: Period length of the continued fraction for sqrt(2^(2n+1)).

A059928.name: The periodic point counting sequence for the toral automorphism given by the polynomial of (conjectural) smallest Mahler measure. The map is x -> Ax mod 1 for x in [0,1)^10, where A is the companion matrix for the polynomial x^10+x^9-x^7-x^6-x^5-x^4-x^3+x+1.
formula: The n-th term is abs(det(A^n-I)) where I is the 10 by 10 identity matrix and A is the companion matrix to the polynomial x^10+x^9-x^7-x^6-x^5-x^4-x^3+x+1.

A059930.name: Numbers n such that n and n^2 combined use different digits.

A059931.name: Numbers n such that n and n^(1/2) combined use different digits.

A059932.name: Prime groupings.
formula: The n-th term of the sequence is determined by grouping the prime numbers according to the natural order of primes themselves, e.g. the first prime is 2 so group the first two primes 2 and 3. Second prime is 3 so group the next 3 primes 5, 7 and 11, etc.

A059933.name: Goodstein sequence starting with 16: to calculate a(n+1), write a(n) in the hereditary representation in base n+2, then bump the base to n+3, then subtract 1.
formula: a(n) = G_n(16), where G is the function defined in A266201.

A059934.name: Third step in Goodstein sequences, i.e., g(5) if g(2)=n: write g(4)=A057650(n) in hereditary representation base 4, bump to base 5, then subtract 1 to produce g(5).

A059935.name: Fourth step in Goodstein sequences, i.e., g(6) if g(2)=n: write g(5)=A059934(n) in hereditary representation base 5, bump to base 6, then subtract 1 to produce g(6).

A059936.name: Fifth step in Goodstein sequences, i.e., g(7) if g(2)=n: write g(6)=A059935(n) in hereditary representation base 6, bump to base 7, then subtract 1 to produce g(7).

A059937.name: Sum of binary numbers with n 1's and two (possibly leading) 0's.

A059938.name: Sum of binary numbers with n 1's and two (non-leading) 0's.

A059940.name: Smallest prime p such that x = n is a solution mod p of x^3 = 2, or 0 if no such prime exists.
formula: If n^3-2 has prime factors > n, then a(n) = least of these prime factors, else a(n) = 0.

A059941.name: Take the n-th number which is just a sequence of 1's and 2's (A007931): if the first k digits in order are the same as the last k digits in order then put 1 in the k-th from right digit of a(n), otherwise put a zero.

A059942.name: A059941 translated from binary to decimal.

A059943.name: Toss a fair coin and calculate the expected time until the n-th possible finite sequence of Heads and Tails first appears (ordered by length of sequence and alphabetical order so H, T, HH, HT, TH, TT, HHH, etc.).
formula: a(n) = 2*A059942(n). For the n-th sequence S (e.g., the 35th is HHTHH), create the set X consisting of subsequences of S which appear both at the beginning and end of S (e.g., X={H, HH, HHTHH}), then a(n) = sum_x(2^length(x)|x is in X) (e.g., a(35)=2^1+2^2+2^5=38).

A059944.name: Denominators of Maclaurin series coefficients for 2*cos(x/sqrt(3) + arctan(-sqrt(3))) = cos(x/sqrt(3)) + sqrt(3)*sin(x/sqrt(3)).
formula: a(n) = 3^floor(n/2)*n! = Product_{k = 1..n}  k*(2 - (-1)^(k-1)) = Product_{k = 0..n-1} A165998(k), with empty products set equal to 1. - _Peter Bala_, Aug 05 2019
a(n) = denominator([x^n] 2*sin(x/sqrt(3) + Pi/6)). Numerator is A057077. - _Peter Luschny_, Aug 07 2019

A059945.name: Number of 4-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: E.g.f. for m-block bicoverings of an n-set is exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1))*Sum_{i=0..inf} x^i/i!*exp(binomial(i, 2)*y).

A059946.name: Number of 5-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: E.g.f. for m-block bicoverings of an n-set is exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1))*Sum_{i=0..inf} x^i/i!*exp(binomial(i, 2)*y).

A059947.name: Number of 6-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1)) * Sum_{i>=0} x^i/i!*exp(binomial(i, 2)*y), for m-block bicoverings of an n-set.

A059948.name: Number of 7-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: The number of m-block bicoverings of an n-set is [x^m*y^n] 1/n!*exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1)) * sum(i>=0, x^i/i! * exp(binomial(i, 2)*y) ) where [x^m*y^n] extracts the coefficient of x^m*y^n, see Goulden/Jackson p.203.

A059949.name: Number of 8-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: E.g.f. for m-block bicoverings of an n-set is exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1))*Sum_{i=0..inf} x^i/i!*exp(binomial(i, 2)*y).

A059950.name: Number of 9-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: E.g.f. for m-block bicoverings of an n-set is exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1))*Sum_{i=0..inf} x^i/i!*exp(binomial(i, 2)*y).

A059951.name: Number of 10-block bicoverings of an n-set.
formula: E.g.f. for m-block bicoverings of an n-set is exp(-x-1/2*x^2*(exp(y)-1))*Sum_{i=0..inf} x^i/i!*exp(binomial(i, 2)*y).

A059952.name: Ordering of a deck of 52 cards after an in-shuffle.

A059953.name: Ordering of a deck of 52 cards after an out-shuffle.

A059954.name: Number of 2 X 2 matrices with elements from {0,1,2,...,n} and with Nim-Determinant 1. (The Nim-Determinant of the 2 X 2 matrix [a,b; c,d] is defined to be a*d xor b*c, where * denotes Nim-Multiplication.)

A059957.name: Sum of distinct prime factors of n and n+1, or number of prime factors of n(n+1) or of lcm(n,n+1).

A059958.name: Smallest number m such that m*(m+1) has at least n distinct prime factors.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = A069354(n) - 1. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Feb 18 2014

A059959.name: Distance of 2^n from its nearest prime neighbor and in case of a tie, choose the smaller.

A059960.name: Smaller term of a pair of twin primes such that prime factors of their average are only 2 and 3.

A059963.name: Triangle T(n,k) giving number of ways of placing n nonattacking queens on n X n board with the queen on the first row fixed at column k, 1<=k<=n.

A059964.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 1, a(n) = a(n-p) + a((n+1)-p), n > 2, where p is the largest prime less than n.

A059965.name: For m>0, each n+m > 5 is expressed as Sum_{k = x,y,z}(pk)_m where (pk)_m is a prime with x <= y <= z; a(n) = largest m such that (pk)_1 = (pk)_2 = ... = (pk)_m.

A059966.name: a(n) = (1/n) * Sum_{ d divides n } mu(n/d) * (2^d - 1).
formula: Inverse Euler transform of A011782. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Jun 23 2018
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)*log((1 - x^k)/(1 - 2*x^k))/k. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 19 2019

A059967.name: Number of 9-ary trees.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies: A = x + A^9.

A059968.name: 10-ary trees.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies: A = x + A^10.
Recurrence: a(0) = 1; a(n) = Sum_{i1+i2+..i10=n-1} a(i1)*a(i2)*...*a(i10) for n>=1. - _Robert FERREOL_, Apr 01 2015
G.f.: RootOf((_Z^10)*x-_Z+1) (Maple notation, from ECS, see links for A007556).
For other family members see the crossreferences.

A059969.name: a(n) = n times the number of letters in n (in English).

A059970.name: Nim-factorials: a(1)=1 and, for n>1, a(n)=n*a(n-1), where * denotes Nim multiplication.

A059972.name: a(n) is the least positive integer k such that all digits of k are 0 or 1 in exactly n different bases B, where 2 <= B <= k; i.e., such that A068953(k)=n.

A059973.name: Expansion of (x + x^2 - 2*x^3) / ( 1 - 4*x^2 - x^4).
formula: Recurrence: a(n) = 4*a(n-2) + a(n-4) for n >= 4; a(0)=0, a(1)=a(2)=1, a(3)=2. - _Werner Schulte_, Oct 03 2015

A059974.name: a(n)=a(p)+a(q) where p and q are the two primes less than n and closest to n; with a(1)=1, a(2)=1.

A059975.name: a(n) is the least number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity) of any integer with n divisors.
formula: a(n) = Sum ( e_i * (p_i - 1) ) where n = Product ( p_i^e_i ) is the canonical factorization of n.
a(n) = row sums of A138618 - row products of A138618. [_Mats Granvik_, May 23 2013]
a(n) = A001414(n) - A001222(n). - _David James Sycamore_, Jul 17 2019

A059976.name: Number of 3 X 3 determinants with elements from {0,...,n} and having the value zero.

A059977.name: a(n) = binomial(n+2, 2)^4.
formula: L(n) = ((n^m)(n + 1)^m)/(2^m) where m is the dimension, which in this case is 4.

A059981.name: Order of compositeness for the n-th composite number.

A059982.name: Symmetric array of numeric partitions related to 1 4 9 16 ... and 1 3 4 7 13 ..., read by rows.

A059983.name: First occurrence of n in A007599.

A059985.name: Łukasiewicz words as integers written in factorial base.

A059986.name: Number of rods required to make a 3-D cube of side length n.
formula: For n > 0, a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} 2*(n+1)(k+n+1), which is the sum of all perimeters of Pythagorean triangles with arms 2*k*(n+1) and (n+1)^2 - k^2 with hypotenuse k^2 + (n+1)^2. - _J. M. Bergot_, May 12 2014

A059989.name: Numbers n such that 3*n+1 and 4*n+1 are both squares.

A059990.name: Number of points of period n under the dual of the map x->2x on Z[1/6].

A059992.name: Numbers with an increasing number of nonprime divisors.

A059993.name: Pinwheel numbers: a(n) = 2*n^2 + 6*n + 1.
formula: a(n) = 4*n + a(n-1) + 4 for n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010

A059994.name: Positions where number of periodic partitions increases.

A059995.name: Drop the final digit of n.
formula: Partial sums are given by A131242. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jun 21 2007

A059998.name: Number of different primes occurring when n is expressed as p1+q1+r1 = ... = pk+qk+rk where pk,qk,rk are primes with pk <= qk <= rk.
formula: If n is of the form 2*(prime + 1) then a(n) is an even number.

A060000.name: If the numbers a(1)...a(n) contain a hole, then a(n+1) is the smallest hole; otherwise a(n+1) = a(n-1) + a(n).
formula: a(k)=k-1 if k>=7 and k <> 2^m * 3 + 4; a(k)=(k-1)*2-3 if k>=7 and k == 2^m * 3 + 4. - _Alfred Heiligenbrunner_, Jun 08 2004
